(In theory, network booting with UEFI is fairly straightforward. Unlike the earlier BIOS based) Tj
T*
(network booting, UEFI defines network booting in the standard itself \(although it's not) Tj
T*
(required\). In practice, vendors of x86 servers have found any number of creative ways to put) Tj
T*
(stumbling blocks in your way in their firmware \(aka 'BIOS'\). Here's an incomplete list of) Tj
T*
(reasons that your server might not be willing to do a UEFI network boot the way you expect it.) Tj
T*
(The firmware might not even be in UEFI mode, in which case at best it's trying to do BIOS PXE) Tj
T*
(boot, which requires a different set of support infrastructure on your boot server that may not) Tj
T*
(be there \( cf , also \). There's no UEFI network booting option \(or options\) in the server's) Tj
T*
(UEFI boot order. The UEFI network boot option is trying to boot from the wrong interface \(on a) Tj
T*
(server with multiple interfaces\). The firmware only supports UEFI network booting using the) Tj
T*
(built-in 1G network interfaces, not with your 10G-T add-in PCIe card that is actually connected) Tj
T*
(to your network. UEFI network booting is enabled in the boot order, but your firmware settings) Tj
T*
(have disabled network booting for all network devices that the firmware will tr...) Tj
